08","ABT 1308":"okolo 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"ABT 1308–":"omkring 1308–Afdød","1305–Male":"1305–Afdød","1300–Male":"1300–Afdød","1308–Female":"1308–Afdød","1305":"1305","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","ABT 1308":"omkring 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"ABT 1308–":"circa 1308–Overleden","1305–Male":"1305–Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1308–Female":"1308–Overleden","1305":"1305","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","ABT 1308":"circa 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1308–":"about 1308–Deceased","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1305":"1305","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","ABT 1308":"about 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Constable","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern): occupational name for the law-enforcement officer of a parish, from Middle English, Old French <i>conestable</i>, <i>cunestable</i>, from Late Latin <i>comes stabuli</i> ‘officer of the stable’. The title was also borne by various other officials during the Middle Ages, including the chief officer of a household or court, or a military officer, and this may in some cases be the source of the surname.","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Constapel</b>, an occupational name for the chief gunner aboard a ship or in the garrison of a fort."],"variants":[{"name":"Costabile","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Antonio, Ciro, Nino, Agnese, Angelo, Duilio, Enrico, Ercole, Franco, Palma.","Italian (southern):","occupational name from medieval Greek <i>kontostablēs</i> ‘chamberlain’, from medieval Latin <i>comes stabuli</i>, literally ‘count of the stable’ (see   Constable  )."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Constable was born about 1308, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Ralph Lascelles."},"et":{"ABT 1308–":"umbes 1308–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1308–Female":"1308–Surnud","1305":"1305","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","ABT 1308":"umbes 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1308–":"noin 1308–Kuollut","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1308–Female":"1308–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","ABT 1308":"noin 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1308–":"environ 1308–Décédée","1305–Male":"1305–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1308–Female":"1308–Décédée","1305":"1305","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","ABT 1308":"environ 1308","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lif